🌓 I had been "out" as queer since around 2006 or 2007. A few friends knew, but that was about it. I didn't hide it, but I wasn't loud about it.

🌓 Like, in the context of the art, the watermark is intended to be overlookable. A link in the body of the tweet is part of the actual content that people are engaging with. They're actively looking at it already. That's the difference.

🌓 They won't even notice that the name was on it! I looked at a piece of art just now and someone pointed the watermark out and only then did I notice it.

If they linked the artist, then it's literally *right there.*

🌓 There are so many things that if it were placed a little closer to you to find, you would look at it. But since it's a little further back, you wouldn't even think of it.

People ignore watermarks when viewing art - most people will never notice that person's name.

🌓 If you read that and say, "Pfft, people are so lazy if that's too many steps" then I hate to break it to you but you also unconsciously avoid things that take more than one or two steps to accomplish on the internet.

🌓 There's like, first you have to be looking for the watermark. Then you have to click to activate the search, type the name in and press enter. Then you have to find that person in the list and click on them. THEN you get to see their work and decide if you want to follow.

🌓 The more barriers you remove between the user and what they want to see, the more users will get to the end point of actually seeing it.

People who would be kind of interested and might later follow might not search it, but they would click a link.

🌓 Idk... I have feelings about light.

🌓 The piece of art that I've made that was most fulfilling was an attempt to capture that image that's been burned into my mind. It didn't come out how I wanted and the frustration is what pushed me through and resulted in something that was deeply moving to make.

🌓 At that exact moment, I realized that abstraction can be used as a way to convey *how* you see, and not just *what* you see. And I realized that the thing that makes me feel so profoundly that I *need* to make art is light, and to a lesser extent color.

🌓 TW: Drugs

The thing that got me to Understand abstraction in art was getting high in the local club, sitting down at the bar and just focusing on one of the red lightbulbs for so long that everything except for the filament turned to blackness.
🌓 I like light and color. If I could set up an easel and paint the city streets on a rainy night I would be so happy. Light makes me feel so many things.
🌓 I don't think I've felt this randomly inspired by something I saw since I got sucked into staring at the tail lights of a car and picking out every detail of each point of light while in traffic.

🌓 There was something entrancing about the long drive of uninterrupted trees on each side, mostly acting as a frame against the sky with frayed edges slowly rippling as I drove past them.

It was inspiring.

🌓 There's a long, straight stretch of road on the way home with trees on both sides. It was just dark enough that the trees were just silhouettes against the sky. The sky was a mess of pinks and oranges and yellows, and the clouds were salmon and looked like snowdrifts.

🌓 Looked at the sky on the drive home this evening and it was gorgeous. I wish I could have taken a picture, but I tried to commit it to memory because it was *absurdly* inspiring and I think I'd like to try to capture it in a painting or something.
